The article discusses the increase in confidence among chief executives of U.S.-based companies, which just experienced one of the largest single-quarter gains in history. This increase is attributed to President Donald Trump's executive order requiring that for every new federal regulation adopted, two old ones must be scrapped. The article emphasizes that this move is seen as a positive step towards reducing the burden of regulations on businesses and stimulating economic growth. The annual cost of regulations in the U.S. is estimated to be $1.9 trillion, which exceeds the amount collected in federal income taxes.